### Step 4: Wire parallel fetch in the upgrade command

In the command's `func()` body:

**Compute `maxItems` from terminal height:**
```typescript
const termHeight = process.stdout.rows;
// Budget: ~1.3x terminal height for the changelog section
// Subtract ~6 lines for the upgrade status/metadata header
const maxItems = termHeight
  ? Math.max(5, Math.floor(termHeight * 1.3) - 6)
  : 30; // sensible default for non-TTY
```

**Parallel fetch:**
- **Upgrade/downgrade path:** Start `fetchChangelog(channel, currentVersion, target, maxItems).catch(() => null)` in parallel with binary download, await after download completes
- **`--check` mode:** Fetch changelog when versions differ (lightweight ŌĆö single API call)
- **`--offline` mode:** Skip (`changelog: undefined`)
- **"up-to-date" result:** Skip ŌĆö no version range

### Step 5: Extend `formatUpgradeResult` in human.ts

After the existing status/metadata/warnings output, render the changelog.

**Approach:** Reconstruct filtered markdown from the `ChangeSection` tokens and pass through `renderMarkdown()`. This ensures the output uses the same rendering pipeline as everything else ŌĆö headings, lists, bold, links all render consistently.

```typescript
function formatChangelog(changelog: ChangelogSummary): string {
  const lines: string[] = [];
  lines.push("### What's new\n");

  const CATEGORY_HEADERS: Record<ChangeCategory, string> = {
    features: "#### New Features Ō£©",
    fixes: "#### Bug Fixes ­¤Éø",
    performance: "#### Performance ŌÜĪ",
  };

  for (const section of changelog.sections) {
    lines.push(CATEGORY_HEADERS[section.category]);
    // Re-serialize the section's tokens back to markdown
    // (subheadings become ##### scope, lists become - items)
    lines.push(tokensToMarkdown(section.tokens));
  }

  if (changelog.truncated) {
    const more = changelog.originalCount - changelog.totalItems;
    lines.push(`\n<muted>...and ${more} more changes</muted>`);
  }

  return renderMarkdown(lines.join("\n"));
}
```

**`tokensToMarkdown(tokens: Token[]): string`** ŌĆö Helper that reconstructs markdown source from AST tokens. For our use case this is straightforward since we only have headings (scope groups) and lists (entries):
- `heading` (depth 4) ŌåÆ `#### text`
- `list` ŌåÆ `- item text` per list item
- Other tokens ŌåÆ `token.raw` (fallback to original text)

This approach means the changelog output gets the full rendering treatment: bold cyan headings, bullet points, code spans, links ŌĆö all consistent with the rest of the CLI's output.

